The patent system has evolved significantly from ancient practices to modern international agreements. It offers exclusive rights to inventors, thereby incentivizing innovation through investments in research and development. However, challenges arise because patents can stifle competition and impose high costs. While concrete statistical analyses remain elusive, historical context and general academic consensus suggest a mixed relationship between patent systems and increased inventiveness. Overall, the patent system can encourage innovation but necessitates careful management to balance inventor rights with broader innovation goals across society.